{{Taxobox | name = Glypheoidea | fossil_range = {{fossil range|Late Permian|Recent|Permo-Triassic–Recent}} | image = Neoglyphea inopinata cropped.JPG | image_caption = ''[[Neoglyphea inopinata]]'' | regnum = [[Animal]]ia | phylum = [[Arthropod]]a | subphylum = [[Crustacean|Crustacea]] | classis = [[Malacostraca]] | ordo = [[Decapoda]] | infraordo = [[Glypheidea]] | superfamilia = '''Glypheoidea''' | superfamilia_authority = [[T. C. Winkler|Winkler]], 1883 }} The '''Glypheoidea''' (containing the '''glypheoid''' lobsters), is a group of [[lobster]]-like [[Decapoda|decapod]] [[crustacean]]s which forms an important part of fossil faunas, such as the [[Solnhofen limestone]]. These fossils included taxa such as ''Glyphea'' (from which the group takes its name), and ''Mecochirus'', mostly with elongated (often semichelate) [[cheliped]]s. This group of decapods is a good example of a [[living fossil]], or a [[lazarus taxon]], since until their discovery in the 1970s, the group was considered to have become [[extinct]] in the [[Eocene]]. The [[Taxonomic rank|superfamily]] Glypheoidea comprises five families. The two extant species, ''[[Neoglyphea inopinata]]'' and ''Laurentaeglyphea neocaledonica'', are both in the Glypheidae.
==Prehistoric abundance== The first animals attributable to the Glypheoidea appeared in the [[Permian|Permo]]-[[Triassic]]. They were abundant in the [[Jurassic]], but declined from the [[Cretaceous]] to the [[Eocene]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=[[Jacques Forest]] |year=2006 |title=Les glyphéides actuels et leur relation avec les formes fossiles (Decapoda, Reptantia) |language=French |trans-title=The Recent glypheids and their relationship with their fossil relatives (Decapoda, Reptantia) |journal=[[Crustaceana]] |volume=79 |issue=7 |pages=769–793 |doi=10.1163/156854006778008212 |url=http://decapoda.nhm.org/pdfs/15941/15941.pdf |format=[[Portable Document Format|PDF]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=[[Jacques Forest]] |year=2006 |title=The Recent glypheids and their relationship with their fossil relatives (Decapoda, Reptantia) |journal=[[Crustaceana]] |volume=79 |issue=7 |pages=795–820 |doi=10.1163/156854006778008221}}</ref>
==Extant taxa== The Glypheoidea was originally considered to be a purely fossil group. That opinion had to be altered when a single male specimen was discovered in the collections of the [[Smithsonian Institution]] in 1975. It had been caught off the [[Philippines]] in 1908 and preserved, without its full significance being realised. Over sixty years later, the specimen was rediscovered, and described by two French scientists as a new genus and species, ''[[Neoglyphea inopinata]]'' in 1975,<ref>{{cite journal |author1=J. Forest |author2=M. de Saint Laurent |year=1975 |title=Présence dans la faune actuelle d'un représentant du groupe mésozoïque des Glyphéides: ''Neoglyphea inopinata'' gen. nov., sp. nov. (Crustacea Decapoda Glypheidae) |journal=[[Comptes Rendus de l'Académie des Sciences, Série D]] |volume=281 |pages=155–158}}</ref> meaning "unexpected new ''Glyphea''". More individuals were caught on subsequent expeditions in 1976, 1980 and 1985, allowing for a complete description.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=J. Forest |author2=M. de Saint Laurent |title=La morphologie externe de ''Neoglyphea inopinata'', espèce actuelle de Crustacé Décapode Glyphéide |work=Rés. Camp. MUSORSTOM, I.Philippines (18-28 mars 1976), 1 (2); Mémoires de l'Office de la Recherche scientifique et technique Outre-Mer |volume=91 |pages=51–84, figs. 1–28 |year=1981}}</ref> A second species was discovered in the [[Coral Sea]], near [[New Caledonia]], in 2005. First described as ''Neoglyphea neocaledonica'', in 2006,<ref>{{cite journal |author=B. Richer de Forges |year=2006 |title=Découverte en mer du Corail d'une deuxième espèce de glyphéide (Crustacea, Decapoda, Glypheoidea) |journal=[[Zoosystema]] |volume=28 |issue=1 |pages=17–28}}</ref> it has been transferred to a new genus ''Laurentaeglyphea'', much closer to fossil forms.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.crvi.2006.08.003 |author=J. Forest |title=''Laurentaeglyphea'', un nouveau genre pour la seconde espèce de Glyphéide récemment découverte (Crustacea Decapoda Glypheidae) |journal=[[Comptes rendus de l'Académie des sciences|Comptes Rendus Biologies]] |volume=329 |issue=10 |year=2006 |pages=841–846 |pmid=17027644}}</ref>
==Classification== [[File:Naturkundemuseum Berlin - Mecochirus longimanatus - Solnhofen.jpg|thumb|upright=0.86|Fossil ''[[Mecochirus longimanatus]]'']] {{Portal|Crustaceans}} Five families are recognised, containing a total of 21 genera, all but two of which are extinct (extant taxa marked in boldface):<ref name="Grave">{{cite journal|journal=[[Raffles Bulletin of Zoology]] |year=2009 |volume=Suppl. 21 |pages=1–109 |title=A classification of living and fossil genera of decapod crustaceans |author1=Sammy De Grave |author2=N. Dean Pentcheff |author3=Shane T. Ahyong |url=http://rmbr.nus.edu.sg/rbz/biblio/s21/s21rbz1-109.pdf |display-authors=etal |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606064728/http://rmbr.nus.edu.sg/rbz/biblio/s21/s21rbz1-109.pdf |archivedate=2011-06-06 |df= }}</ref>
{{col-begin|width=auto}} {{col-break}} *† [[Chimaerastacidae]] :*† ''[[Chimaerastacus]]'' *'''[[Glypheidae]]''' :*† ''[[Cedrillosa]]'' :*† ''[[Glyphea]]'' :*'''''[[Laurentaeglyphea]]''''' :*'''''[[Neoglyphea]]''''' :*† ''[[Paralitogaster]]'' :*† ''[[Squamosoglyphea]]'' :*† ''[[Trachysoma]]'' {{col-break}} *† [[Mecochiridae]] :*† ''[[Huhatanka]]'' :*† ''[[Jabaloya]]'' :*† ''[[Mecochirus]]'' :*† ''[[Meyeria]]'' :*† ''[[Preatya]]'' :*† ''[[Pseudoglyphea]]'' :*† ''[[Selenisca]]'' {{col-break}} *† [[Pemphicidae]] :*† ''[[Pemphix]]'' :*† ''[[Pseudopemphix]]'' :*† ''[[Sinopemphix]]'' *† [[Platychelidae]] :*† ''[[Glaessnericaris]]'' :*† ''[[Platychela]]'' :*† ''[[Platypleon]]'' {{col-end}} {{Clear}}
