An adult female between the age of twenty-five and thirty-five years old was discovered wrapped in plastic and concealed in a [[Footlocker (luggage)|footlocker]] on  October 31, 1969 in St. Petersburg, Florida. The murder weapon, a tie, was visible around her neck. Examination also concluded she had suffered blunt force trauma to the head. The murder had taken place within seventy-two hours of her discovery. She was five feet nine inches tall, weighing 130 pounds, she was the mother of at least one child, and the dental care she received in her life was relatively low, despite the fact that her wisdom teeth had been removed.<ref name="Case File 661UFFL">{{cite web| title=Case File 661UFFL|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/661uffl.html| publisher=The Doe Network| accessdate=May 8, 2014}}</ref> Her face has been reconstructed twice, including by the University of South Florida.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 1019|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/1019|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=November 29, 2014|date=April 8, 2008}}</ref>

=="Little Miss Lake Panasoffkee"==

{{main|Little Miss Lake Panasoffkee}}

The body of a young woman was found in the summer of 1971 underneath a bridge. She had been killed by [[strangulation]]. Analysis of the remains traced her place of residence to a village in [[Greece]]. She had given birth to at least two children between the ages of 17 and 24 years. Evidence of various dental work and a unique ankle surgery were present on the body, which may indicate she was from a well-off background. Reconstructions were created between 1971 and 2012.<ref name="Sullivan">{{cite news|url=http://www.thevillagesdailysun.com/articles/2006/10/08/news/news02.txt |title=Little Miss Panasoffkee |first=Dan |last=Sullivan |newspaper=The Village's Daily Sun |accessdate=October 7, 2006 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last= |title=LITTLE MISS "P" |url=http://unsolved.com/ajaxfiles/mur_little_miss_p.htm |accessdate=April 8, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121121123101/http://unsolved.com/ajaxfiles/mur_little_miss_p.htm |archivedate=November 21, 2012 }}</ref>

{{anchor|Volusia County John Doe}}

==Volusia County John Doe==

[[File:Volusia County John Doe shoe.jpg|thumb|left|Shoe worn by the Volusia County John Doe]]

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1224409c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
| image2 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1224409x3.jpg Profile]
| image3 = [https://www.namus.gov/api/CaseSets/NamUs/UnidentifiedPersons/Cases/13620/Images/37671/Original Digital reconstruction]
| image4 = [https://www.namus.gov/api/CaseSets/NamUs/UnidentifiedPersons/Cases/13620/Images/37672/Original Profile]
| image5 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1224409x2.jpg Shirt]
}}

The body of a male aged eleven to fourteen was found floating in a pond on May 7, 1972 in Daytona, Volusia County, Florida. He had been stabbed to death three to four days before and was already decomposed when he was found, preventing the assessment of his eye color. The victim was white at a height of five feet two inches tall and weighed around 110 to 120 pounds. He had dark wavy hair and had no evidence of dental work, but his teeth were in very good condition. On his right leg, a [[benign tumor]] was found and the bones of his feet had fused together. Both of these traits were caused by different conditions but would not likely have symptoms. The victim also may have shaved his pubis, if he was at a reproductive stage in his life.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 2128UMFL|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/2128umfl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=March 11, 2015|date=January 17, 2015}}</ref> He wore a denim jacket, a red and white striped shirt, gray pants, brown socks and one black shoe with a silver buckle. The latter articles of clothing were presumed to be dress clothes. The boy had a wallet with visible paint drops in his back pants pocket, although it is unknown if it assisted with finding clues about the victim's identity. The body was exhumed in 2013 to collect DNA.<ref>{{cite web|year=2014|title=John Doe 1972|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1224409/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]]|accessdate=March 11, 2015}}</ref>

{{anchor|Seminole County Jane Doe}}

==Seminole County Jane Doe==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184260c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
| image2 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1184260x2.jpg Profile]
| image3 = [https://www.namus.gov/api/CaseSets/NamUs/UnidentifiedPersons/Cases/1341/Images/46926/Original University of South Florida reconstruction]
}}

The body of an unidentified white female was found on August 21, 1973. She was likely between the ages of 13 and 18 but may have been as old as 21. It was believed that she may have been a victim of Joseph Spaziano.

She was found within a wooded area beneath the body of Laura Harbers, whose murder Spaziano was later charged with. A witness claimed to have met a teenage girl in Daytona Beach, Florida, who was riding on a motorcycle with Spaziano. The girl asked the witness to watch over her purse until she returned. When the girl did not return, the witness looked through the purse but could only recall to authorities that the girl may have been from [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]]. Five days later, Spaziano returned and took the purse from the witness.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 67UFFL|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/67uffl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=August 17, 2014}}</ref>

Seminole County Jane Doe was slenderly built, being between 5 feet 1 inch and 5 feet 7 inches tall.  She weighed about 110 pounds. She had light brown hair tied in a ponytail.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1973|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184260/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=August 17, 2014}}</ref> Some of her teeth may have been found at the scene.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case Report - NamUs UP # 1341|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/full_report/1341|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=August 17, 2014|date=April 8, 2008}}</ref>

{{anchor|Marion County John Doe}}

{{anchor|Miami-Dade County Jane Doe (1979)}}

==Miami-Dade County Jane Doe (1979)==

[[File:1979 Miami Jane Doe.jpg|thumb|150px|The Miami-Dade County Jane Doe may be an Ohio runaway named Tina with the nickname "Sheeba."]]

On September 4, 1979, a young woman's body was found lying in an apartment complex parking lot next to a  dumpster in Dade, Miami-Dade County, Florida. She was believed to have died just hours before, leaving her face in a recognizable condition. She had not been murdered at that location and had likely been killed at a different area.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case # 258983-Z (1979)|url=http://www.miamidade.gov/police/cold-cases/1970-1979/cc-258983-z.asp|website=www.miamidade.gov|date=April 9, 2012|publisher=Miami-Dade Police Department|accessdate=November 24, 2014}}</ref> Her eyes were described to be hazel, although the [[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]] states that they were a grayish-green.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 7514|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/7514|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=November 24, 2014|date=August 5, 2010}}</ref> Her hair was strawberry blond and she was at a height of five feet five to five feet eight inches tall with a weight of 120 pounds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 791UFFL|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/791uffl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=November 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Tuey|first1=Holly|title=Woman found in FL in 1979 believed to be Ohio runaway|url=http://www.toledonewsnow.com/story/25989136/woman-found-in-fl-in-1979-believed-to-be-ohio-runaway|accessdate=November 24, 2014|work=Toledo News Now|agency=Worldnow and WTOL|date=July 10, 2014}}</ref> She was between seventeen and twenty-five years old at the time of her death. On her calves, burns were found, possibly from coming in contact with tail pipes from riding on a motorcycle.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kilpatrick|first1=Mary|title=Ohio woman found dead in Miami in 1979 remains unidentified|url=http://www.cleveland.com/metro/index.ssf/2014/07/ohio_woman_found_dead_in_miami.html|accessdate=November 24, 2014|work=Cleveland.com|agency=Northeast Ohio Media Group|publisher=Plain Dealer Publishing Company|date=July 10, 2014}}</ref> The victim also had acne on her face and some fillings in her mouth. The body was found clad in a white tee shirt, a yellow scarf with flower designs and blue jeans. Recent developments in her case have turned up the possibility that she may have been an Ohio runaway named Tina with the nickname "Sheeba."<ref>{{cite news|title=Authorities need help IDing woman found dead 35 years ago|url=http://www.wkyc.com/story/news/local/ohio/2014/07/10/missing-woman/12489593/|accessdate=November 24, 2014|work=WKYC News|publisher=NBC|date=July 16, 2014}}</ref> However, no information has been published if this lead has had results.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1979|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184167/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=November 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Woman found dead in Florida in 1979 may have been missing from Ohio|url=http://www.wcpo.com/news/state/state-ohio/woman-found-dead-in-florida-in-1979-may-have-been-missing-from-ohio|accessdate=November 24, 2014|work=WCPO News|publisher=Scripps TV Station Group|date=July 10, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129190109/http://www.wcpo.com/news/state/state-ohio/woman-found-dead-in-florida-in-1979-may-have-been-missing-from-ohio#|archive-date=November 29, 2014|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The missing girl had left Ohio in 1977 and has never been seen or heard from since.<ref>{{cite news|title=Police learning more about murder mystery|url=http://wdtn.com/2014/07/15/police-learning-more-about-murder-mystery/|accessdate=November 24, 2014|publisher=TVL Broadcasting LLC|work=WDTN News}}</ref> The [[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]] published this information on their Facebook page dedicated to unidentified children, hoping for additional tips.<ref>{{cite web|title=New lead in unidentified case generates publicity|url=https://storify.com/missingkids/digital-media-update-july-11-2014|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=November 24, 2014|year=2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Broward County John Doe (1979)}}

==Broward County John Doe (1979)==
[[File:Broward John Doe 79.jpg|thumb|left|150px|1979 Broward County John Doe]]

On November 2, 1979, a young white man was killed by a drunk driver while walking on Interstate 95 in Fort Lauderdale, Broward County, Florida. The victim was killed alongside another individual who was later identified.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 1298UMFL|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/1298umfl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=December 13, 2014}}</ref> He was between sixteen and twenty-five years of age at a height of {{convert|5|ft|5|in|cm|spell=in}} and a weight of {{convert|208|lb|kg}}. His eyes were light in color, as they were gray.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 1310|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/1310|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=December 13, 2014|date=April 8, 2008}}</ref> The victim's hair was brown and he also may have had facial hair, although this is unknown. He was fully clothed at the time of his death but little detail exist on the exact color or brand of his clothing. He had no evidence of seeing a dentist in his life, as he had no fillings or other sorts of work.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Doe 1979|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1127671/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]]|accessdate=December 13, 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Volusia County Jane Doe (1980)}}

==Volusia County Jane Doe (1980)==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [https://www.namus.gov/api/CaseSets/NamUs/UnidentifiedPersons/Cases/724/Images/941/Original NCMEC reconstruction]
| image2 = [https://www.namus.gov/api/CaseSets/NamUs/UnidentifiedPersons/Cases/724/Images/942/Original Profile view]
}}

A young woman's remains were found in Daytona Beach, Volusia County, Florida on November 5, 1980. She was murdered several weeks before and had most likely died due to stab wounds that occurred in her upper torso. The victim was a prostitute, according to convicted murderer Gerald Eugene Stano, who stated he choked the victim, instead of stabbing her, and had met her a few years before she was found dead. She was likely Hispanic, although she could have been White/Black biracial as well.<ref name=doev>{{cite web|title=Case File: 382UFFL|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/382uffl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=January 5, 2015|date=October 28, 2014}}</ref> She was estimated to be between fifteen and twenty five years old, to have been subjected to labor that involved using her arms, had been between five feet seven to five feet eleven inches tall and weighed between 115 and 135 pounds.<ref name=ncmecv>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1980|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184261|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=January 5, 2015|date=2014}}</ref> Her height and weight ranges were difficult to estimate, as her skeleton was partial.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 724|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/724|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=January 5, 2015|date=November 9, 2007}}</ref> She had fillings that contained a metal that had been outdated at the time. She also had some teeth that had been removed as well as some that never developed. She wore a red shirt, green shoes and a red pair of shorts. She also had a handkerchief and twenty-seven cents in her possession.<ref name=doev/> Her face was digitally reconstructed by the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children in 2014.<ref name=ncmecv/>

==Miami-Dade County Jane Doe (1981)==

[[File:Jane Doe 1981 Florida.jpg|thumb|left|150px|1981 Miami-Dade County Jane Doe]]

A female of African ancestry aged sixteen to twenty-six was discovered within a day of her death on February 3, 1981 in Miami-Dade County, Florida. The female had been beaten to death, as numerous injuries were noted on her body and was then left in a Japanese Garden. She was clothed, wearing a "white/beige shirt," blue jeans and white undergarments, the bottoms with the words "Rest Area Visitors Welcome." The young woman had a gap between her two front incisors and she had bleached her black hair blonde in some places. She was estimated to be five feet and two inches tall and to have weighed 90 pounds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 790UFFL|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/790uffl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 7963|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/7963|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=July 4, 2015|date=March 16, 2010}}</ref>

{{anchor|Glades County Jane Doe}}

==Glades County Jane Doe==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [https://www.namus.gov/api/CaseSets/NamUs/UnidentifiedPersons/Cases/7915/Images/20639/Original Digital reconstruction]
| image2 = [https://www.namus.gov/api/CaseSets/NamUs/UnidentifiedPersons/Cases/7915/Images/20640/Original Profile view]
}}

A white woman's body was found floating in a canal in Moore Haven, Glades County, Florida, on March 9, 1981, approximately one day after she was killed by a blow to the side of her head. Although she had died recently, her body was already decomposing and was unrecognizable.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 7915|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/7915|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=November 29, 2014|date=September 28, 2010}}</ref> The victim may have been seen earlier at two local restaurants before her death. She was between twenty-five and forty-five years old, wearing a pink shirt, a white bra, jeans, blue knee-high socks and brown ankle-high boots. The letter N was tattoed amateurishly on the top of her right thumb, which may have represented her or a loved one's name.<ref>{{cite web|title=Glades Florida Jane Doe March 1981|url=http://canyouidentifyme.org/GladesFloridaJaneDoeMarch1981|website=canyouidentifyme.org|accessdate=November 29, 2014}}</ref> The woman had painted her toenails with a copper-colored polish but not on her fingernails. This is possibly due to her being a nail-biter, as her nails were chewed short. She had hazel eyes with auburn hair and she was between five feet four to five feet six inches tall as a weight of approximately 125 pounds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 509UFFL|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/509uffl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=November 29, 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|South Bay John Doe}}

==South Bay John Doe==

[[File:South Bay, FL John Doe 1984.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Most recent reconstruction of the South Bay John Doe]]

On February 3, 1984, the skeleton of a male aged seventeen to twenty-eight was found in South Bay, Palm Beach County, Florida. It is believed that he had died within a year of his body being found. The victim was approximately five feet nine inches to six feet tall with a weight at around 110 to 130 pounds. He was found clothed; he wore blue underwear underneath a pair of white swim trunks and white socks with a blue stripe. Analysis of his bones indicated he had broken some ribs weeks before his murder and he had also suffered trauma to his right hand that failed to heal properly, which may have distorted the way his thumb looked. The young man had fillings in his teeth and had one of his back teeth extracted a year or more before.<ref>{{cite web|year=2015|title=John Doe 1984|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184443/1/screen|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]]|accessdate=July 2, 2015}}</ref> The cause of death was ruled as homicide, as he had been struck with a blunt object in the back of his head. His hair was brown and was somewhat curly.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File: 18UMFL|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/18umfl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Netowork]]|accessdate=July 2, 2015|date=May 5, 2015}}</ref> One missing person, Terry Stokes, has been excluded from the case.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 814|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/814|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=July 2, 2015|date=January 18, 2008}}</ref>

{{anchor|Broward County Jane Doe}}

==Broward County Jane Doe==

[[File:1984 Davie JaneDoe Reconstruction 004b.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Broward County Jane Doe]]

The body of a young, white woman, aged eighteen to thirty five, was located face-down in a canal in Davie, Broward County, Florida on February 18, 1984. The woman wore only shorts, although the possibility of her being sexually assaulted has not been confirmed. The Jane Doe stood at five feet four inches and was 120 pounds with curly blond or strawberry blond hair and hazel eyes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case Report - NamUs UP # 1258|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/full_report/1258|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=September 17, 2014|date=April 8, 2008}}</ref> She had a gap between her front teeth, which may pose an important role in identifying her.<ref>{{cite web|title=Unsolved Homicide|url=http://www.davie-fl.gov/Pages/DavieFL_NewPoliceDept/Investigations/UnsolvedPDFs/JaneDoe.pdf|website=davie-fl.gov|publisher=Davie Police Department|accessdate=September 17, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141223022717/http://www.davie-fl.gov/Pages/DavieFL_NewPoliceDept/Investigations/UnsolvedPDFs/JaneDoe.pdf#|archive-date=December 23, 2014|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She had been strangled around two days before her body was located. It is possible that she was murdered by [[Christopher Wilder]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 554UFFL|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/554uffl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Altoona Jane Doe}}

==Altoona Jane Doe==

[[File:Altoona Jane Doe.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Sketch of the Altoona Jane Doe]]

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [https://www.namus.gov/api/CaseSets/NamUs/UnidentifiedPersons/Cases/6037/Images/18766/Original NCMEC reconstruction]
| image2 = [https://www.namus.gov/api/CaseSets/NamUs/UnidentifiedPersons/Cases/6037/Images/18765/Original Three quarter view]
| image3 = [https://www.namus.gov/api/CaseSets/NamUs/UnidentifiedPersons/Cases/6037/Images/18768/Original Profile]
}}

On April 18, 1984, a seventeen to twenty-year-old female was found in the woods in Altoona, Lake County, Florida, several weeks after she died. Her remains were severely decomposed and had mostly been skeletonized. She was approximately 5.0' to 5.1' tall and weighed between 90 and 110 pounds. The victim had straight light brown to auburn hair and is believed to be white. She wore a black shirt reading "here comes trouble," a whitish shirt with the words "have you kissed your child tonight?", jeans, tan shoes with blue trim, tan underwear and a gold necklace.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 126UFFL|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/126uffl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=December 16, 2014}}</ref> She may have fractured two of her ribs during her life, which may assist in identifying her.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 6037|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/6037|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=December 16, 2014|date=October 16, 2009}}</ref> It is known that her left ear was pierced but she wore no earring when found. Decomposition prevented knowing if the other ear was pierced. She had also painted her nails a coral or orange-red. After a dental exam, she was found to have been missing two teeth on the top jaw and had some that were discolored a reddish-purple color. The victim may have been new to the area, as initial reports state.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1984|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1184243/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing & Exploited Children]]|accessdate=December 16, 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Broward County John Doe (1985)}}

==Broward County John Doe (1985)==

{{for|the unidentified vehicular accident victim|Broward County John Doe (1979)}}

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [https://www.namus.gov/api/CaseSets/NamUs/UnidentifiedPersons/Cases/1240/Images/296/Original Sketch]
}}

A man was found on March 12, 1985 in Fort Lauderdale, Broward County, Florida, shortly after his death.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 1240|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/1240?page=case_information|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=December 15, 2014}}</ref> He was murdered and left in a hotel room by two people, who were convicted in his murder. The man was between twenty-one and thirty-five years of age when he died and was five feet eight inches tall, weighing 181 pounds. The John Doe had brown hair, brown eyes and a mustache and was possibly of French origin, but this has not been confirmed. Although he was found naked, a blue shirt and tan pants were found in the room.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 185UMFL|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/185umfl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=December 15, 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Dade County John Doe}}

==Dade County John Doe==

[[File:Miami John Doe 1988.jpg|thumb|left|150px|Artist's rendering of the Dade County John Doe]]

On January 5, 1988, the body of a young male was discovered inside of a hotel room in Miami, Dade County, Florida. The victim, ages sixteen to twenty-one, was five feet six inches and weighed 145 to 153 pounds. The boy had blond hair, gray or brown eyes and had scars on his wrists, hands and on his right thigh. Claiming he was a foster child native to New York selling magazines, the John Doe had given some his name, Robert Copland, with associated nicknames. However, investigators are unable to verify that it was his actual name.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 662UMFL|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/662umfl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=August 17, 2014}}</ref> The boy wore a white shirt with a flag design, jeans and ankle-high socks. No dental fillings or signs of orthodontic treatment were observed, as his teeth were described to have appeared fairly healthy.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Doe 1988|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1111149/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=August 17, 2014}}</ref> He was previously believed to have been missing person Chester Wetmore, but he was ruled out after their fingerprints were compared.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 1212|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/1212|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=August 17, 2014|date=April 8, 2008}}</ref>

{{anchor|Wilderness Park John Doe}}

==Wilderness Park John Doe==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [https://identifyus.org/en/medias/full/11027 3D reconstruction]
}}

The remains of a man of African descent (originally believed to be Asian)<ref>http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/533umfl.html</ref> were found in Wilderness Park, [[Hillsborough County, Florida]] on March 14, 1988. He stood between five feet five and five feet six inches tall, his weight unknown due to [[skeletonization]], his age estimated between twenty-eight and thirty-four years old. He was found wearing a tee shirt reading "Drunken State" and jeans, and possessed a blue [[wallet]]. A cause of death has not been determined, although he was believed to have been murdered. His face was [[forensic facial reconstruction|reconstructed]] by artist Wesley Neville, who has created several other reconstructions of other unidentified people.<ref name="Case File 533UMFL">{{cite web| title=Case File 533UMFL| publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/533umfl.html| accessdate=April 21, 2014}}</ref><ref name="ReferenceB">{{cite web| title=Hillsborough Florida John Doe March 1988|url=http://canyouidentifyme.org/HillsboroughFloridaJohnDoeMarch1988| accessdate=April 21, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Case Report - NamUs UP # 201">{{cite web|title=Case Report - NamUs UP # 201|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/full_report/201|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=July 27, 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Julie Doe}}

=="Julie Doe"==

[[File:Julie Doe.jpg|thumb|150px|Reconstruction of Julie Doe]]

The badly decomposed remains of a transgender woman, aged between 22 and 35 were discovered at the roadside in Lake County, Florida on September 25, 1988. The victim was initially believed to be a [[cisgender]] woman until DNA testing indicated she was [[biologically]] male at birth. The body had been "dragged" to a concealed area and the pantyhose she wore had been partially removed. She additionally wore a bluish-green tank top and an acid-washed denim skirt.<ref>{{cite web |title=2752UMFL |url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/2752umfl.html |website=www.doenetwork.org |publisher=[[The Doe Network]] |accessdate=September 27, 2018 |date=May 1, 2016}}</ref> The cause of death was never determined, yet investigators suspect she was murdered due to the circumstances surrounding her discovery.<ref name=orlando>{{cite news |last1=Hayes |first1=Christal |title=New sketch released: Do you recognize this transgender woman? |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/breaking-news/os-transgender-woman-composite-sketch-1988-20151121-story.html |accessdate=September 27, 2018 |work=OrlandoSentinel.com |date=November 21, 2015}}</ref> <ref name=cis>{{cite news |title="Julie Doe" - Transgender woman likely murdered in 1988, believed to be cisgender for 27 years |url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2015/11/19/1451910/--Julie-Doe-Trans-woman-likely-murdered-in-1988-believed-to-be-cis-for-27-years |accessdate=September 27, 2018 |work=Daily Kos |date=November 19, 2015}}</ref> She had died about eight months before her discovery.<ref>{{cite web |title=Unidentified Person Case |url=https://www.namus.gov/UnidentifiedPersons/Case#/6030 |website=www.namus.gov |publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]] |accessdate=September 27, 2018 |language=en |date=October 14, 2009}}</ref>

Julie Doe had breast implants, the type had been discontinued around 1983.<ref name="cis" /> There was also evidence she had a [[rhinoplasty]]. Her hair was long and bleached blond and had long fingernails that were manicured. Additionally, a healed fracture was visible on one of the cheekbones, toes and one of the ribs and possibly her nose.<ref>{{cite news |title=New Sketch of "Julie Doe", Transgender Woman Still Unidentified After 27 Years |url=https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2015/11/21/1452995/-New-Sketch-of-Julie-Doe-Transgender-Woman-Still-Unidentified-After-27-Years |accessdate=September 27, 2018 |work=Daily Kos |date=November 21, 2015}}</ref> Additionally, she was taking hormone replacement drugs.<ref name=orlando/> She is believed to have undergone gender confirmation surgery around 1984, perhaps in Atlanta, Georgia, Miami, Florida, New Orleans, Louisiana, New York, New York or perhaps California.<ref name="cis" /> She was around 5'11 at a weight between 150 and 180 pounds.<ref>{{cite news |title=Do you know this woman? Police release sketch of transgender victim in cold case - Watermark Online |url=http://www.watermarkonline.com/2015/11/30/do-you-know-this-woman-police-release-sketch-of-transgender-victim-in-cold-case/ |accessdate=September 27, 2018 |work=Watermark Online |date=November 30, 2015}}</ref>

The DNA Doe Project took on the case but initial attempts to extract DNA from the bones proved unsuccessful. The organization later began funding for a third attempt in November 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Transgender Julie Doe |url=http://dnadoeproject.org/case/transgender-julie-doe/ |publisher=[[DNA Doe Project]] |accessdate=15 November 2018}}</ref>

{{anchor|Valentine Doe}}

=="Valentine Doe"==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1103868c1.jpg NCMEC reconstruction]
| image2 = [http://api.missingkids.org/photographs/NCMU1103868x1.jpg Profile view]
| image3 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/49UFFL.jpg Digital reconstruction]
}}

[[File:Valentine Doe 1993 Comp.jpg|thumb|left|150px|1993 reconstruction of Valentine Doe]]

{{commons category|Valentine Doe}}

{{distinguish|Valentine Sally}}

The body of a sixteen to twenty-five-year-old female was found on February 15, 1991, one day after her death in [[Big Coppitt Key]], [[Monroe County, Florida]], located in the [[Florida Keys]]. She had been [[strangulation|strangled]], beaten and left in the woods in the [[Bahia Honda Key|Bahia Honda]] State Recreation Area.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Doyle|first1=Chris|title=Authorities seek ID of murder victim|url=http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v247/suzannec4444/Tammy/monroecounty1.jpg|accessdate=October 20, 2014|agency=The Key West Citizen|date=February 17, 1991}}</ref><ref name=two>{{cite news| title=Two Jane Does|url=http://www.wsvn.com/story/23072516/two-jane-does| accessdate=May 1, 2014| newspaper=WSVN News| date=August 7, 2013}}</ref> Authorities also suspect that she may have been [[rape]]d.<ref name="Case File 49UFFL">{{cite web| title=Case File 49UFFL|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/49uffl.html| publisher=The Doe Network| accessdate=April 29, 2014}}</ref> The victim wore multiple [[earring]]s in each ear, had dark eyes and brown hair as well as two tattoos, one being a heart on her left arm reading "love" and the other a small cross on the left hand. She likely wore a striped blue and red sweater, jeans, and moccasins decorated with turquoise beads, which were found near the body. The clothing that she wore indicated she was not from the area, as well as the fact that she didn't have any tan lines. Other distinguishing characteristics include stretch marks on her stomach and [[cyst]]s present on her [[Fallopian tube]]s and [[ovary|ovaries]]. She may have also been [[pregnant]] at one time in her life.<ref name=two/> The victim was five feet four inches and weighed 145 pounds. Her face and clothing were reconstructed into a [[composite image]] in 1993 and was later reconstructed by the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children.<ref name="Unsolved Homicides: Jane Doe">{{cite web| title=Unsolved Homicides: Jane Doe|url=https://www.fdle.state.fl.us/Content/Office-of-Statewide-Intelligence/Homicides/Jane-Doe-(2).aspx| publisher=Florida Department of Law Enforcement| accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref> Her case was featured on ''[[America's Most Wanted]]''.<ref name="Case File 49UFFL"/>

{{anchor|Sorrento Jane Doe}}

==Sorrento Jane Doe==

[[File:Sorrento FL Jane Doe Reconstruction 3f.jpg|thumb|150px|left|A woman found in Sorrento, Florida was wearing very distinct earrings but was never identified]]

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/412UFFL.jpg Sketch]
}}

{{commons category|Sorrento Jane Doe}}

In Sorrento, Lake County, Florida, a woman's body was discovered on December 7, 1991. She had been murdered approximately twelve hours prior and had been raped and was naked below the waist. She was between five feet four to five feet five inches tall and weighed between 120 and 125 pounds. Her hair was brown with blond-dyed ends. She wore a sweatshirt, sports bra and a pink and blue top. Her teeth were healthy and her eyes hazel; she had bore at least one child and possibly another. Although she had also been tortured, the victim,  aged twenty-five to thirty-five, was killed by strangulation. Her face was recognizable and she wore unique earrings with gold-colored heart and star shapes, but was never identified, her killer was arrested and charged for her murder, but did not know her name.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 412UFFL|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/412uffl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=September 17, 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Palm Beach County Jane Doe}}

==Palm Beach County Jane Doe==

[[File:Palm Beach County Jane Doe.jpg|thumb|150px|The Palm Beach County Jane Doe had an abnormality in her lower spine, which may have impacted the way she walked.]]

A skeleton of a female between sixteen and twenty years old was found hidden under brush on August 28, 1993 in the [[Everglades]], near the border between Palm Beach and Broward Counties. She was around five feet one to five feet five inches and was approximately one hundred pounds.<ref>{{cite web|title=White Female Found in West Palm Beach Saturday, August 28, 1993|url=http://www.pbso.org/index.cfm?fa=unidentifiedvictims&id=23|publisher=Palm Beach Police Department|accessdate=August 30, 2014|year=2009}}</ref> Men's shorts and a large boot were worn by the young woman. No other clothing or the cause of her death were discovered. She had an abnormality in her spine which may have caused difficulties when walking. The female was dead for up to two years.<ref name="Case File 43UFFL">{{cite web|title=Case File 43UFFL|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/43uffl.html|publisher=The Doe Network|accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> Currently, three people have been ruled out as a possible identity of the decedent.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case Report - NamUs UP # 1138|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/full_report/1138|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=August 30, 2014|date=April 8, 2008}}</ref>

{{anchor|Palm Beach County John Doe}}

==Palm Beach County John Doe==

[[File:PB John Doe.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Palm Beach County John Doe]]

A white male between thirty-six and forty-five years of age (some sources say as young as twenty-five) was discovered skeletonized on October 25, 1993. He was murdered by a blow to the head.<ref name="Case File 98UMFL">{{cite web|title=Case File 98UMFL|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/98umfl.html|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Specific Case">{{cite web|title=Specific Case|url=http://www.fluiddb.com/php/details10.php?case=373|publisher=Florida Unidentified Decedents System|accessdate=May 16, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140517123003/http://www.fluiddb.com/php/details10.php?case=373#|archive-date=May 17, 2014|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Other physical descriptions include that one of his legs was not as long as the other and he had previous damage to his nose and spine. The clothing he wore read "Road Kill Cafe, You Kill It, We Grill It." He also had long brown hair.<ref name="NamUs UP # 1135">{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 1135|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/1135|publisher=NamUs|accessdate=May 16, 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Baby Belle}}

=="Baby Belle"==

[[File:Baby Belle.jpg|thumb|150px|Sketch of "Baby Belle"]]

The decomposing remains of an infant were found on May 23, 1996 in Clewiston, Hendry County, Florida. The child was female, approximately one to one and a half feet tall and weighed around five pounds. Her body was concealed in a multicolored blanket that appeared to be made in a Mexican or Native American design. The baby was white with Hispanic characteristics, as she had dark hair. Also at the scene, four other blankets, a red bucket and a sweater were located.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jane Doe 1996|url=http://www.missingkids.org/poster/NCMU/1111186/1#poster|website=missingkids.org|publisher=[[National Center for Missing and Exploited Children]]|accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 1112|url=https://identifyus.org/cases/1112|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=December 23, 2014|date=April 8, 2008}}</ref> The infant was approximately three weeks to two months old when she died several days before her body was found by a man collecting cans along a road, which was near [[US 27]].<ref>{{cite web|title=White Female Found in Clewiston|url=http://www.pbso.org/index.cfm?fa=unidentifiedvictims&id=24|publisher=Palm Beach County Sheriff's Office|accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref> Her case is being treated as a murder, as her lower and upper jaws were fractured. Her footprints were compared to many taken at local hospitals but none matched.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 160UFFL|url=http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/160uffl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=December 23, 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Bay County Jane Doe}}

==Bay County Jane Doe==
{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/images/150UFFL.jpg 3D reconstruction]
}}

The remains of a white woman, possibly native to the [[Czech Republic]], were found on May 30, 1996 in Southport, Bay County, Florida. She was between five foot six to five foot nine inches tall, but her weight was not possible to estimate, although she was of petite build. Examination of her body indicated that she may have been in a vehicular accident when she was alive, as there were healed fractures on her nose, knee and ribs. Some of her teeth were also missing. Her hair was light brown, wavy and had blond highlights and she wore a gold bracelet, a bluish pullover and a sports bra. She was approximately twenty-one to thirty-five years old.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case Report - NamUs UP # 1111|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/full_report/1111|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=August 30, 2014|date=April 8, 2008}}</ref> A woman matching the victim's description was seen on April 20, 1996 with a man leaving a gentleman's club. The man, Billy Frank Hansen, was convicted of second-degree murder of the woman, who he confessed to raping and murdering after he agreed to drive her home. The victim was apparently heavily intoxicated and stated that she would have sexual intercourse with Hansen if he paid her. These events took place on April 20 of the same year.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 150UFFL|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/150uffl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref>

{{anchor|Hillsborough County John Doe (1998)}}

==Hillsborough County John Doe (1998)==

{{external media
| align  =
| width  =
| image1 = [http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/images/478UMFL.jpg 3D reconstruction]
| image2 = [http://doenetwork.org/cases/images/478UMFL4.jpgProfile]
| image3 = [http://www.doenetwork.org/cases/images/478UMFL5.jpg Sketch]
}}

A black male, clothed only in shorts, was unearthed from a shallow grave on April 6, 1998 in Plant City, Hillsborough County, Florida. The victim had been shot with a shotgun and was then wrapped in a carpet after his murder earlier in the 1990s. Raymond Crocker went on trial for the murder after the body was found and his wife confessed to assisting him with disposing the body in 1994. She claimed that her husband murdered the man in [[Zephyrhills, Florida]] because he was in debt to the victim for cocaine.<ref>{{cite web|title=Case File 478UMFL|url=http://doenetwork.org/cases/478umfl.html|website=doenetwork.org|publisher=[[The Doe Network]]|accessdate=December 27, 2014}}</ref>
The victim was between twenty-five and forty-five years old and was five feet seven to five feet nine inches tall and weighed around 180 pounds.<ref>{{cite web|title=NamUs UP # 185|url=https://identifyus.org/en/cases/185|website=identifyus.org|publisher=[[National Missing and Unidentified Persons System]]|accessdate=December 27, 2014|date=June 30, 2007}}</ref>

