'''Manius Acilius Aviola''' was a [[Roman senate|senator]] of the [[Roman Empire]]. He was ''[[Roman consul|consul ordinarius]]'' in AD 54 with [[Marcus Asinius Marcellus]] as his colleague. Aviola is also recorded as being governor of [[Asia (Roman province)|Asia]] in 65/66.<ref name=CIL>{{CIL|6|1331}}</ref> According to Brian Jones, Aviola was also ''[[curator aquarum]]'' (or "superintendent of the aqueducts") from 74 to 97.<ref>Brian W. Jones, ''The Emperor Domitian'' (London: Routlege, 1993), p. 51</ref> He is known almost solely from surviving inscriptions.

Aviola has been identified as the son of [[Gaius Calpurnius Aviola]], suffect consul of AD 24.<ref name=CIL/> Assuming that he became consul ''anno suo'', he would have been born around AD 22, making this relationship more likely. He is known to have lived into [[Domitian|Domitian's]] reign, and that he married Aedia Servilia, the daughter of [[Servilius Nonianus|Marcus Servilius Nonianus]] (consul AD 35).<ref>Paul Gallivan, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/4435641 "Who Was Acilius?"], ''[[Historia: Zeitschrift für Alte Geschichte]]'', 27 (1978), p. 622</ref> Older authorities, such as [[Edmund Groag]], have identified Aviola with the Avilius mentioned by [[Juvenal]],<ref>''Satires'', iv.94-96</ref> but Gallivan has argued that Aviola is a different person.<ref>Gallivan, "Who was Acilius?", p. 623</ref> 

Although it is not known if Aviola had any children, there is a [[Manius Acilius Aviola (consul 82)|Manius Acilius Aviola]], suffect consul in 82, who is sometimes identified as his son, and [[Manius Acilius Aviola (consul 122)|Manius Acilius Aviola]], ordinary consul in 122, who is sometimes identified as his grandson.

