'''Schizophyte''' was a botanical [[Taxonomy (biology)|classification]] proposed by [[Ferdinand Cohn]] to describe the class of primitive "plants" that reproduce solely by [[binary fission|fission]].<ref>{{citation |last= Cohn |first= Ferdinand |title= Organismen in der Pockenlymphe |journal= Virchows Archiv |volume= 55 |issue= 1 |pages= 229–238 |year= 1872 |language= German |doi=10.1007/bf01937204}}</ref> It has been considered synonymous with the [[Protophyta]] of [[Julius von Sachs|Sachs]] and the [[Monera]] of [[Ernst Haeckel|Haeckel]].<ref>{{cite journal |last= Gibbons |first= N.E. |last2= Murray |first2= R.G.E. |title= Proposals concerning the higher taxa of bacteria |journal= International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology |volume= 28 |issue= 1 |pages= 1–6 |year= 1978 |doi=10.1099/00207713-28-1-1}}</ref> In modern taxonomy, it is equivalent with the concept of [[prokaryote]]s, single-celled microorganisms with no nucleus or other membrane-bound organelles, now divided into the domains [[Bacteria]] and [[Archaea]].

